column168: AT 7:50 PM, SATURDAY, JUNE 30, 1984, THE C-2 YARD ASSIGNMENT, WHILE SWITCHI NG ON THE NORTH YARD, CAUSED SULFURIC ACID TO SPLASH OUT OF THE TOP CAP OF GATX 77733 AND ONTO BRAKEMAN M.L. DOYLE.  MR. DOYLE WAS TRANSPORTED TO RICH MOND MEMORIAL HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  T ANK CAR WAS MOVED TO NO. 20 TRACK, NORTH YARD, TO ISOLATE THE CAR AND TO MA KE IT MORE ACCESSIBLE FOR REPAIRS.  AT 10:00 AM, SUNDAY, JULY 1, 1984, MECH ANICAL DEPARTMENT FORCES INSPECTED THE CAR AND DIAGNOSED THE PROBLEM TO BE A DEFECTIVE TOP CAP SEAL.  AT 10:30 AM, CHEMTREK WAS NOTIFIED AND CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, ESSEX CHEMICAL, IN NEWARK, NEW JERSEY.  AT 11:12 AM, MR. PRUD ENTE WITH ESSEX CHEMICAL CALLED AND WAS ADVISED OF OUR CIRCUMSTANCES AND HE AGREED TO ARRANGE FOR REPAIRS.  MR. PAUL WILLIAMS WITH THE BUREAU OF EXPLO SIVES CALLED AT 11:20 AM, REQUESTED INFORMATION AND ADVISED THAT THERE WAS A BUREAU REPRESENTATIVE IN ALEXANDRIA IF NEEDED.  DALE DAVIS, BUREAU OF EXP LOSIVES, ALEXANDRIA, VIRGINIA REPRESENTATIVE, CALLED AT 11:30 AM AND OFFERE D HIS ASSISTANCE.  MR. DAVIS WAS PATCHED THROUGH TO CHEMTREK WHO COORDINATE D EFFORTS WITH ESSEX CHEMICAL.  ESSEX CHEMICAL AGREED TO HAVE MR. DAVIS MAK E THE NECESSARY REPAIRS.  THE VIRGINIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICE WAS NOTI FIED AT 11:50 AM.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER(PETTY OFFICER WALLACE) WAS NOTIFIED AT 12:05 PM.  AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 PM, JULY 1, 1984, DALE DAVIS, DISTRICT INSPECTOR FOR THE BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, ARRIVED AT ACCA YARD AND M ADE HIS INITIAL INSPECTION OF TANK CAR GATX 77733.  THE INSPECTION REVEALED THE 18-INCH MANWAY COVER WAS UNSECURED, THE GASKET FOR THE MANWAY WAS FOUND LYING ON TOP OF THE MANWAY COVER AND A 12-INCH LONG EXTENSION PIPE ON THE VAPOR LINE PREVENTED SECUREMENT OF THE MANWAY COVER BOLT.  THE LIQUID AND VAPOR EDUCTION PIPES WERE NOT IN A PRO TECTIVE HOUSING AND THE HANDLES WERE STILL ATTACHED.  MR. DAVIS ADVISED THAT THE TANK CAR HAD APPARENTLY LEFT ESSEX CHEMICAL CO PLANT IN THE ABOVE CONDITION.  MR. DAVIS REMOVED THE 12-INCH-LONG EXTENSION PIPE, PLACED THE GASKET ON THE MANWAY, PROPERLY CLOSED AND SECURED THE MANWAY COVER AND REPLACED THE 12-INCH EXTENSION PIPE.  HE ALSO REPLACED THE RUPTURE DISC WHICH WAS HEAVILY CORRODED AND REMOVED THE HANDLES FROM THE LIQUID AND VAPOR EDUCTION PIPES.  THE REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED BY 4:00 PM AND AT 5:30 PM, THE TANK CAR WAS MOVED BACK AND FORTH TO DETERMINE IF THE TANK CAR WAS STILL LEAKING.  IT WAS NOT.  AT 5:45 PM, THE TANK CAR WAS REMOVED FROM NO. 20 TRACK AND PLACED IN SERVICE.  AT 8:57 AM ON JULY 2, 1984, THE TANK CAR DEPARTED ACCA YARD ON THE SEABOARD SYSTEM RAILROAD'S ROCKY MOUNT LOCAL.
